@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

 Introduction
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~

 I was tempted to call PSpool, SPS v2.0. In fact pspool.rexx is the result
 of many modifications to sps.rexx, but it does so much more than its
 predecessor that I felt it was not right to give it the same name. The
 name does not even begin to describe its functionality. In the docs for
 SPS I said that;
 
 "Samba Print Spooler (SPS from here onwards) is an ARexx script which
 automates the process of sending print jobs from an Amiga running Samba to
 a SMB print server - for example a PC running Windows 95/98/NT."

 However PSpool is able to spool any file from any directory to another
 local directory (either fixed or set "on the fly" via a reqtools file
 requester), to a networked share (file) or a networked printer.

 Unlike SPS which could only handle one printer, when combined with
 PSwitch, PSpool can spool files to an unlimited number of printers or 
 directories. Even if you only have one printer you can use PSwitch to
 create different profiles, all of which can be switched between within
 seconds thanks to the MUI graphical user interface. 

 I have successfully tested PSpool using a wide selection of standard
 Workbench drivers and TurboPrint versions 5 and 7. To my knowledge there
 are no known incompatibilities.

@endnode

@node "Requirements" "Requirements"

 Requirements
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~

 PSpool requires the following items;

  * For networked printing you will need a working installation of Samba
    (this requires a TCP/IP stack such as MiamiDx or Genesis). If you
    need any help installing Samba then please take a look at my web site.

  * rexxtricks.library

  * reqtools.library

  * rexxreqtools.library

  * rexxsupport.library

  * rexxmast

  * An Amiga driver for the printer (selected in 'sys:prefs/printer' or
    'turboprint:turboprefs')

  * CMD (normally found in your sys:utilities directory)

  * The AmigaDOS "delete" command in C:

  * The AmigaDOS "copy" command in C:

  * For multiple device/profile support you must also install PSwitch
    (included in this archive). Read the PSwitch docs, for PSwitch's
    requirements.

@endnode

@node "Operation" "Operation"

 Operation
 ~~~~~~~~~

 PSpool utilises CMD to "grab" the print data sent to the parallel port and
 then send it to a file. This file is written in a directory that is checked
 every 10 seconds by PSpool. When PSpool finds a file in this directory, it
 checks to see if it can get an exclusive lock on the file. If it can't get
 a lock then the script assumes that the print data is still being spooled
 to the file and therefore waits another 10 seconds before checking again.

 When the script gets a lock on the file it is spooled to the local
 directory, networked file share or networked printer.

 Spooling to a local directory is done using the AmigaDOS "copy" command.

 Spooling to a networked file share is done using "smbclient". The following
 command is issued;

   amitcp:samba/bin/smbclient \\\\server\\fileshare -P -U username%password

 Once connected the following command is issued;

   put "spoolfile" "spoolfile"

 Spooling to a networked printer is done using "smbclient". The following
 command is issued;

   amitcp:samba/bin/smbclient \\\\server\\printer -P -U username%password

 Once connected the following commands are issued;

   setmode graphics
   print "spoolfile"

 Note that "graphics" print mode isn't just for graphics, but for any binary
 data. Therefore all files which have been "printed" to a file with the
 Amiga printer driver will be sent as "graphics".

@endnode

@node "Installation" "Installation"

 Installation
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~

 1) Check that rexxmast is installed/running.

 2) Copy pspool.rexx to somewhere (rexx: would be good).

 3) Install rexxtricks.library, reqtools.library, rexxreqtools.library and
    rexxsupport.library in libs:

 4) To enable the 'auto retry' feature install autoclose.rexx. Read the
    docs for autoclose.rexx that are in the script header. Load the script
    into your favorite text editor/reader.

 5) Set the options found in pspool.rexx's header. Load the script into your
    favorite text editor.

@endnode

@node "BOptions" "Basic options"

 Basic options
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~

 For simple usage, printing to a single networked printer leave all settings
 between "START SET DEFAULTS" and "END SET DEFAULTS" alone.

 printers = 1

 Set to the number of printers on your network that you want to use. Leave
 this set to 1.

 cmdpath = 'sys:utilities/cmd'

 Where can PSpool find CMD? This setting is used by both 'setcmd' and
 'runcmd'.

 runcmd = 1

 It is preferable to let PSpool start CMD. Setting this to 1 will allow
 PSpool to start CMD for you. This is highly recommended. When PSpool 
 starts CMD all parameters are set via CLI arguments.

 setcmd = 0

 Set to 1 if you want PSpool to set CMD's tooltypes. It is not required to
 set this option if "runcmd" is set to 1. If you are running CMD from
 WBStartup then pspool.rexx should be started before 'loadwb' in your
 startup-sequence or user-startup. However 'rexxmast' must obviously be
 running before that. You don't have to do this, but if you don't then
 PSpool will change the settings after CMD has been run and therefore will
 have no effect until a reboot. Save yourself lots of hassle and just set
 "runcmd" to 1 and leave/move CMD in/to sys:utilities/.

 pubscreen = 'Workbench'

 The name of the public screen where all requesters should open on. Do not
 set this to '' otherwise PSpool will fail! 

 username. = 'username'

 Set this to your username on the print server. If not required (e.g. on a
 Win95/98 server set to ''

 password. = 'password'

 Set this to your password on the print server. If not required (e.g. on a
 Win95/98 server set to ''

 spooldir.1 = 'Data:spool/'

 Set this to your spool folder. This dir/drive/assign name MUST end in ":"
 or "/". Also the set path MUST be dedicated to the function of spooling
 files to the printer as ANYTHING found in this folder will be sent to the
 printer!

 Note that the spool folders path must NOT contain spaces. This is a
 limitation of rexxtricks GETDIR() function.

 printer.1 = '\\\\dynamix\\DESKJET'

 The printer name in the form of '\\\\server\\printer'. Note that on Windows
 (95/98/NT) servers the printer name is ALWAYS UPPER CASE.

@endnode

@node "AOptions" "Advanced options"

 Advanced options
 ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
 
 Advanced usage is not that advanced. However to show first time users all
 these options I thought that it might scare them off - hence the "Basic
 options" section.

 DEFAULT SETTINGS:

 All the settings in this section set the default settings for ALL
 spooldirs. Exceptions to these defaults must be defined with each printers
 settings. The default settings must be defined before the individual
 printers.

 exclude. = 0

 When set to 1 this option tells PSpool to exclude (not check for files) ALL
 spooldirs. Probably best left as 0. To exclude a specific spooldir (for
 example printer.3) set "exclude.3 = 1"

 extension. = ''

 This option has no effect when printing to a printer. By this I mean, not a
 local or networked directory. See "service." for an explanation of this
 options usage.

 pattern. = '~(#?.info)'

 This is the default AmigaDOS pattern used when scanning spooldirs. As you
 probably know this means - "anything but files which end in .info". Lets
 say you only want printer.2 to spool files that start with "Fred" then set
 "pattern.2 = 'Fred~(#?.info)'". I'm not sure quite what use this option is,
 however it seemed like a good idea at the time ;-)

 purge. = 0

 When set to 1 PSpool will purge (delete) ALL files in all spooldirs on
 startup. Use this with caution! Don't set your spooldir to "sys:" otherwise
 you'll be in for a shock! This option was added to remove icons (.info)
 from spooldirs that have been spooled to using something other than CMD
 (CMD doesn't create icons), such as printing as a Postscript file (direct
 to the spooldir) using Final Writer. I suggest you leave this as 0 and
 purge specific spooldirs. For example to purge printer.4, set "purge.4 = 1".

 service. = 'printer'

 Sets the default networked (this option has no effect on local services)
 service type (printer or file share) to 'printer'. To copy print data to a
 networked file share set to 'file'. For example, "service.5 = 'file'".

 When a service is set as 'file' or the printer is a local directory then
 the "extension.n" (where 'n' is the printer number) setting is checked by
 PSpool. If "extension.n = ''" then the file is always renamed with a unique
 filename (extension of ".prn") during spooling to prevent duplicates.

 However lets suppose that "extension.n = 'ps'". In this case all files that
 DON'T have the "ps" extension will be renamed with a unique filename and
 given an extension of ".ps". All files that DO have the "ps" extension
 will be spooled without renaming.

 subdir. = ''

 This option is only checked when "service.n = 'file'". Set this to the sub
 directory on the specified file share (printer.n) where files should be
 spooled to. For example "subdir.5 = 'data\\distiller\\in'"

 GLOBAL SETTINGS:

 printers = 3

 Set to the number of printers on your network that you want to use. Spool
 dirs are checked in order from 1 to 'x'. If you want to exclude a specific
 spooldir for checking then use "exclude.n".

 cmdpath = 'sys:utilities/cmd'

 Where can PSpool find CMD? When using more that 1 printer, PSpool does not
 start CMD, but still passes this setting to PSwitch.

 For PSwitch to work correctly then it must have total control over the
 starting of CMD and therefore when printers > 1 the "runcmd" and "setcmd"
 settings are ignored.

 pubscreen = 'Workbench'

 The name of the public screen where all requesters should open on. Do not
 set this to '' otherwise PSpool will fail! 

 username. = 'username'

 Set this to your default username on the network. If not required (e.g. on
 a Win95/98 server set to ''. If a specific printer requires a different
 username then simply set "username.n = 'different_username'".

 password. = 'password'

 Set this to your default password on the network. If not required (e.g. on a
 Win95/98 server set to ''. If a specific printer requires a different
 password then simply set "username.n = 'different_password'".

 PRINTER SETTINGS:

 The following settings are required for each printer, where 'n' is 1, 2, 3,
 4, etc....

 spooldir.n = 'Data:spool/'

 Set this to your spool folder. This dir/drive/assign name MUST end in ":"
 or "/". Also the set path MUST be dedicated to the function of spooling
 files to the printer as ANYTHING found in this folder will be sent to the
 printer!

 Each printer MUST have it's OWN spooldir! This is very important. Ensure
 that the spool dir exists as PSpool will not create it for you.

 Note that the spool folders path must NOT contain spaces. This is a
 limitation of rexxtricks GETDIR() function.

 printer.n = '\\\\dynamix\\DESKJET'

 The printer name in the form of '\\\\server\\printer'. Note that on Windows
 (95/98/NT) servers the printer name is ALWAYS UPPER CASE.

 To spool files to another local folder then simply set printer.n as the
 path (ending in ':' or '/'). For example "printer.2 = 'ps:'". 
 If running GhostScript on the Amiga you could share spooldir.2 as a file
 share on the network and PSpool will then spool all files copied to this
 share to the PS: device ;-) Useful eh!?

 If printer.n = '?' then a reqtools file requester will open asking you
 where to save the print data. This is useful if you want to create a
 printer profile in PSwitch that prints to FILE: - useful if you've got a
 nice colour laser at work ;-)

@endnode

@node "Usage" "Usage"

 Usage
 ~~~~~

 From the shell type "rx pspool" (without the quotes). This is assuming that
 pspool.rexx is installed in rexx:. Otherwise you will need to specify the
 path, e.g. "rx network:rexx/pspool".

 Once you know it works (as if it won't eh!?) add the command to your
 user-startup, startup-sequence, "startnet" script or just start from the
 shell etc as required. Hey, this is the Amiga you can do it however you
 like ;-)

 If starting from a script remember that PSpool doesn't detach itself and
 therefore probably should be started something like;

   run <>nil: sys:rexxc/rx rexx:pspool.rexx

@endnode

